<text>
    <group>
       
    
    <!-- type is letter -->

    
        
        <pb n="6389" facs="#L1916_2303_img_6389"/>
            <text type="letter" decls="#corresp1">
                <body>
                    

<lb/>to expect </p>
<p> I had tea with the sapper Craig yesterday . He is a 
<lb/>nice chap &amp; seems fairly satisfied about Charles being all
<lb/>right. He was left for 8 days in our old area when the
<lb/>Division moved &amp; &amp; spoke guardedly but very strongly about
<lb/>the difference between our men &amp; theirs, &amp; there is no 
<lb/>doubt in my mind that we <del>shall get a</del> cannot expect
<lb/>anything from future elements in comparison with the original
 <lb/>new armies who were inspired by partition. The swarms
<lb/>of unwilling conscripts will undoubtedly swamp the old
<lb/> type by being saved till the end instead of being
<lb/>mixed with them in moderate quantities earlier. </p>
<p>I must not let this letter end without lifting up
<lb/>the <del>wrap</del>  curtain a little to the p v, to let her peep under &amp; see
<lb/>what a very different bw is behind thanks to her help.
<lb/>She knows this jolly well but never objects being told ! 
<lb/>It is a beautiful summer day when we could have a
<lb/>great romp, I don't think the weather will matter
<lb/>much when we are together again. I'm glad your work
<lb/>  is a little less &amp; that the money is coming in for you
<lb/>must need it all. By the way some of our Ulster Div men  
<lb/><del>may</del> now have been transferred to other Divisions but you
<lb/>will of course look after them just the same.</p>
 <opener><salute>Your b w</salute>
 <signed>WB Spender</signed></opener>
        
    

    
         
        <pb n="6396" facs="#L1916_2303_img_6396"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>the whole empire work at full stretch &amp; no half measures <add>it is no good going on.</add></p>
 <p>I look upon our present action as absolutely inadequate
<lb/>&amp; think we shall get into a worse instead of a better position
<lb/>if things drift on, &amp; that unless we can make our minds
<lb/>at once to tighten up every screw it would be better to
<lb/>finish at once. I have less confidence in the Government
<lb/>now that ever before &amp; really think that unless Sredward
<lb/>does what he told you he can do he had better let them
<lb/>give terms which I understand are now <del>obtainable</del> dictatable. </p>
<p>As you know I am not a pessimist but as things
<lb/>stand now it seems to me that Balfour is trying to make
<lb/>the nation face what we are really up against instead of
<lb/><unclear>mistaking</unclear> our costly success was taking the most patriotic
<lb/>course. The present policy of partial effort will mean a 
<lb/>far more inconclusive finish <del>when</del> than is now possible
<lb/>when every one has come to the end of their resources,
<lb/>except our Yankee cousins. </p>
<p>Some of our men will be in the trenches again tomorrow 
<lb/>and it is only a matter of days before we follow. I cannot of 
<lb/>course tell <del>wh</del> you what part of the country we are in, but
<lb/>it is more fertile &amp; the people nicer that I had been led
        
    
         
        <pb n="6397" facs="#L1916_2303_img_6397"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>being moved at 1 days' notice, as if it didn't care what 
<lb/>happened to our battalions &amp; men who had to march but
<lb/>protested about our precious <unclear>selves</unclear> who have motors &amp;
<lb/>lorries. G also supported old S that I ought to protest
 <lb/>against the inconvenience but C who is a soldier at any
<lb/>rate, said that if we did not move to the new place
<lb/>someone else would &amp; that we should then be between
<lb/>2 stools, so I carried my way but not pleasantly. Old 
<lb/> S is as selfish as they make them &amp; pampers <add>selfishness</add> in others,
<lb/>&amp; will get promoted in consequence. Perhaps he earns it for it 
<lb/>must be unpleasant </p>
<p>I think you have caught the newspaper optimism. If
<lb/>you get the chance tell Sredward that in my view the
<lb/>situation is much more critical than it has been for a 
<lb/>year past &amp; that partial success now means another
<lb/> year's delay &amp; then equally no progress at the present
<lb/> rate of preparation. I would go further &amp; say that unless
<lb/>the nation is prepared at once to redouble its efforts, making
        
    
         
        <pb n="6400" facs="#L1916_2303_img_6400"/>
        
        
           
            <closer><date>21 July 1916</date>
<salute>My pr</salute></closer>
<p>I have just got your <hi rend="underline">extra nice</hi> letter. You by all 
<lb/>means tell the family or any one you like, provided that it 
<lb/>does not lead to an appeal which tho' kindly intended
<lb/> would make me very angry, &amp; would almost certainly do
<lb/> more harm than good. Anyhow I would not attempt one
<lb/> myself nor any explanation. If one year's intercourse 
<lb/>cannot absorb one from their kind of misunderstandings I'm
<lb/>hanged if it is worthwhile attempting any reconciliation.</p>
<p>I am not sure now who has done this stupidity, whether 
<lb/>G.C. Wrawfor or so I think Genl P. <del>to</del> <add>via</add> Sir G.. Perhaps 
<lb/>it is as well. All of them have behaved in a peculiar way, 
<lb/>but I like them too well to cause them the great
<lb/><sic>distain</sic> which they would feel if they knew.</p>
<lb/>Old fat S rather enjoys stirring up mud &amp; began to 
<lb/>run me down for being too polite to the Corps etc at 
<lb/>dinner. "You ought to be firm". The thing that I had not 
<lb/>been firm about was in not protesting against Div H A
        
    
                </body>
